title: Brandy
discription: This brandy is made from grapes in the Cognac region of Southwest France.

title: Brandy
discription: It's an alcoholic beverage made from the leftover grapes during winemaking.

title: Gin
discription: It's an alcoholic beverage made from the leftover grapes during winemaking.

title: Brandy
discription: Calvados is exclusively made in the Normandy region of France and can be made from apples as well as pears.

title: Brandy
discription: Applejack is made from apples such as Winesap.

title: Brandy
discription: It's an alcoholic beverage made from the leftover grapes during winemaking.

title: Gin
discription: Bombay Sapphire is a ubiquitous and easy-drinking gin

title: Gin
discription: Tanqueray is one of the best-selling gins in the world, and a superb (and affordable) example of the London Dry category.

title: Gin
discription: Beefeater is another classic London dry gin, with a juniper- and citrus-forward recipe that dates back to the 1860s when James Burrough began to distill gin in London.

title: Gin
discription: Plymouth Gin has been produced at the historic Black Friar’s Distillery since the late 18th Century.

title: Gin
discription: Gordon’s was reputed to be Hemingway’s favorite gin, and it was an essential ingredient in James Bond’s Vesper cocktail in Casino Royale

title: Gin
discription: Hendrick’s has been one of the biggest success stories in the new-school gin movement since it launched in 1999.

title: Gin
discription: Monkey 47 is already an interesting gin, made at a distillery in Germany’s Black Forest from a blend of 47 botanicals.

title: Gin
discription: This gin hails from New Mexico, where it’s made at the Altar Spirits distillery in Santa Fe. The label says “high desert American gin,” a pretty accurate way of describing this interesting new addition to the category.

title: Gin
discription: Ireland is awash with excellent gin, and Drumshanbo is leading the way there with its Gunpowder Gin.

title: Gin
discription: Speyside is a region of Scotland best known for single malt whisky, but this gin is an attempt to capture the local herbs and flowers of the area in gin form.

title: Gin
discription: Purity hails from Sweden, a country better known for aquavit than gin. But this navy strength expression, bottled at a very strong 57.1% ABV, could help change that.

title: Gin
discription: The founders of this California gin were inspired by the long nautical journey of the gray whale off the coast of the Golden State.

title: Gin
discription: This African gin is part of the Spearhead spirits family, a Black-owned company based in South Africa.

title: Gin
discription: This French gin is the creation of Maison Ferrand owner and master blender Alexandre Gabriel.

title: Rum
discription: Barbadoss Mount Gay has been around in one form or another for about 300 years (Remy Cointreau has owned the distillery since 1989).

title: Rum
discription: This Dominican rum brand was founded in 1930, but has come a long way since then. The distillery is now a carbon-neutral operation that makes rum from sugarcane grown by local farms and plantations.

title: Rum
discription: Appleton Estate master blender Joy Spence believes there should be two categories of rum: flavored rum (with sugar) and true rum (no sugar added).

title: Rum
discription: Alexandre Gabriel, owner of Maison Ferrand, takes a cue from his native France for his Plantation Rum brand.

title: Rum
discription: Holmes Cay is focused on one thing releasing the best single cask rum it can find, with no sugar or adulterants added.

title: Rum
discription: Diplomático is produced in Venezuela from molasses and sugarcane honey, which the distillery describes as “the syrup left over after the first boiling of sugarcane,” with a higher sugar content than molasses.

title: Rum
discription: The rum produced on the island of Martinique is known as rhum agricole–instead of using molasses to make the spirit, sugarcane juice is fermented and distilled into something that is familiar but decidedly different.

title: Rum
discription: Bacardi may be the biggest distillery in Puerto Rico, but Destileria Serralles makes what might be the most popular rum as far as the locals are concerned–Don Q.

title: Rum
discription: Brugal is another Dominican rum, and its core 1888 expression is double aged in both bourbon and sherry casks (kind of like many single malt whiskies) to develop its flavors.

title: Rum
discription: The whiskey scene is full of independent bottlers and blenders, and this model has gained traction in the rum world as well.

title: Rum
discription: This is a newer brand that was founded by Caribbean native Marc Farrell, who wanted to create rum blends sourced from reputable distilleries that did not use sugar, color, or additives for flavor.

title: Whiskey
discription: Teeling was the first whiskey distillery to operate in Dublin in about 125 years when it opened back in 2015.

title: Whiskey
discription: Bushmills and Jameson are both extremely palatable and inexpensive Irish blends, but there are some big differences, not the least of which is that Bushmills is produced in Northern Ireland.

title: Whiskey
discription: There’s a lot of history behind this Irish whiskey brand, which like Bushmills is produced in Northern Ireland. McConnell’s, which calls Belfast home, is a blend of sourced malt and grain whiskey that’s aged for about five years in ex-bourbon barrels.

title: Whiskey
discription: Midleton Very Rare is made at the eponymous distillery run by Irish Distillers just outside of Cork, the same place where brands like Jameson, Redbreast, and Powers are made.

title: Whiskey
discription: You might not be aware that Redbreast is distilled at the same massive distillery as Jameson, but indeed the two are produced at Midleton just outside of Cork, along with a few other notable brands. Redbreast is a shining example of a single pot still Irish whiskey.

title: Whiskey
discription: Some of the most interesting new Irish whiskeys available in the US come from Waterford, a distillery focused on showcasing the effects of terroir on whiskey.

title: Whiskey
discription: Slane is owned by Brown-Forman, the company behind the whiskey juggernaut that is Jack Daniel’s. The brand, founded by Alex Conyngham and his family, is located on the grounds of Slane Castle where his father Henry has put on legendary rock concerts for years.

title: Whiskey
discription: This distillery isn’t too far away from the much larger Midleton just outside of Cork, but it’s making its own way in the rapidly growing world of Irish whiskey.

title: Whiskey
discription: This is one of two whiskey brands that come from parent company Walsh Whiskey (the other being The Irishman). Writers’ Tears is a blend of pot still and single malt whiskey, with no grain whiskey included in the makeup.

title: Tequila
discription: Patrón helped define the premium tequila category when it launched over a quarter century ago.

title: Tequila
discription: Casa Noble is one of several organic-certified tequila brands, but that’s not why it’s good. No, this is good tequila because it’s a crisp, spicy, flavorful, and very versatile spirit.

title: Tequila
discription: El Tesoro, part of the Beam Suntory family, has a long history dating back to the 1930s. From blanco to añejo, El Tesoro produces excellent sipping tequilas, with vegetal notes that play nicely with the sweet agave undercurrent.

title: Tequila
discription: Espolòn, part of the Campari America family, is an inexpensive tequila option that sips far beyond its price point wih prominent notes of agave and spice.

title: Tequila
discription: These days, it wouldn’t be a tequila roundup without at least one celebrity-backed brand on the list. And one of the best in that category is Codigo 1530. Country music legend George Strait is the star power behind the brand, although admittedly his stake is relatively small.

title: Tequila
discription: This tequila launched in 2019, and is made from a “Hi/Lo” blend of agave grown in the Highlands and the Lowlands of Jalisco. According to the brand, each brings different unique flavors to the palate - fruitier, sweeter notes from the Highlands, pepper and spice from the Lowlands. There are three expressions available, a blanco, reposado, and anejo.

title: Tequila
discription: Latitude Beverage, the company behind Wheel Horse Whiskey, came out with this new tequila brand a few years ago, starting off with a blanco expression. More recently, a reposado was released, aged for three to four months in ex-bourbon barrels.

title: Tequila
discription: This brand, owned by the Stoli Group, launched a few years back in 2018. Master distiller Arturo Fuentes brings a long history in tequila, as well as experience in cognac, to the table for this brand which has a lineup of aged expressions, a cristalino, and the new Ahumudo.

title: Tequila
discription: This luxury brand, which was also founded by Richard Betts, currently has a lineup of three tequilas: Anejo Cristalino, aged for a year in French oak white wine barrels before being filtered; Reposado Rosa, aged for 65 days in French red wine barrels to infuse it with pink color and fruit flavors; and Extra Anejo, aged in both wine and whiskey barrels.

title: Tequila
discription: This new brand comes from Campari, the company that owns the eponymous bright red amaro as well as Wild Turkey and Espolon.

title: Vodka
discription: This Scottish spirit is the world’s first blended barley vodka — and it’s possibly unlike anything you’ve tried before. The initial aroma is full-on floral with a sweet, toasted barley backbone.

title: Vodka
discription: As we’ve covered, the birthplace of vodka remains fiercely debated, with both Russia and Poland claiming to be progenitors of the spirit. While the jury is out, there’s no denying that Belvedere is a fine example of Polish vodka-making traditions (600 years, no less).

title: Vodka
discription: Bottled in London, this potato-based vodka is complex and creamy, with an intriguing botanical profile of juniper, citrus peel and black pepper. We'd recommend keeping it simple with a vodka martini, though it’s versatile enough for other cocktails, too.

title: Vodka
discription: Made from the finest French ingredients – soft winter wheat and Gensac spring water filtered through Grande Champagne limestone – it’s exceptionally well-balanced with a fresh, herbaceous flavour and a hint of rye.

title: Vodka
discription: Nikka set the bar with its Japanese whisky, but this vodka is just as impressive, with a characteristically sweet profile due to the unique Coffey still distillation process.

title: Vodka
discription: This Irish vodka packs a real punch, opening with sweet baked spice, vanilla and plenty of black pepper heat. Like other characterful vodkas, Boatyard forgoes filtration to allow for full-on flavour and a moreish mouthfeel.
